<article>
    <h1>BAN HENG NASI LEMAK AND FRIED BEE HOON</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201227/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-27"><time>2020-12-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WHERE 01-62 Al­bert Cen­tre Mar­ket and Food Cen­tre, 270 Queen Street</p>
    <p>OPEN 6.30am to 9.30pm</p>
    <p>Sat­isfy all noo­dle crav­ings at this stall, which of­fers five types of fried noo­dles. Better yet, en­joy up to 25 side dishes as Ban Heng sells both nasi lemak and econ­omy bee­hoon.</p>
    <p>On top of the usual fried bee­hoon ($1), fried mee ($1) and kway teow ($1), the stall also serves Hokkien mee ($1) and mee goreng ($1). A yuan yang or­der of two types of noo­dles costs $2. Or­der four types on a plat­ter for $3, which is good for shar­ing.</p>
    <p>Stall owner Low Yin Kok, 56, who is a big noo­dle fan, grew up in Gey­lang Serai, eat­ing the mee goreng and nasi lemak cooked by his Malay neigh­bours. The flavour­some fare made a last­ing im­pres­sion on him and in­flu­enced his style of cooking.</p>
    <p>His Hokkien mee is a pared-down ver­sion with no prawn stock, but its sim­plic­ity makes it suit­able for break­fast. The laksa bee­hoon and fat yel­low egg noo­dles are twice-fried in small batches to in­fuse the strands with aro­mas of the wok.</p>
    <p>The full range of noo­dles and dishes is avail­able at 7am. But each batch of Hokkien mee and mee goreng gets sold out in min­utes.</p>
    <p>Mr Low is par­tic­u­larly proud of his sam­bal petai ($2), which con­tains potato cubes and ikan bilis.</p>
    <p>An­other must-or­der is the chicken wings. The large wings are mar­i­nated overnight in gin­ger juice and gar­lic. The crust is crispy from a blend of rice flour, potato starch and self-rais­ing flour. A word of cau­tion, though: Eat­ing one sparks the de­sire to have an­other and an­other.</p>

